{"cursor":"23105","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Mir Murtaza Bhutto ÙÙØ± ÙØ±ØªØ¶Û Ø¨Ú¾Ù¹Ù image =\n| MMurtazaBhutto_1.jpg image_size = alt = caption = birth_name = birth_date =\n| birth_place = Karachi, Pakistan death_date = death_place = Karachi, Pakistan\n| cause = Police encounter resting_place = Garhi Khuda Baksh, Sindh, Pakistan\n| alias = allegiance = Al-Zulfiqar motive = Overthrow of Zia regime charge =\n| Airplane hijacking Terrorism conviction = 1981, by military tribunal\n| conviction_penalty = Death conviction_status = occupation = Politician spouse\n| = Fauzia Fasihuddin Bhutto Ghinwa Bhutto parents = Zulfikar Ali\n| Bhutto Nusrat Bhutto\n}} 'Mir Ghulam Murtaza Bhutto' (18 September 1954 â 20 September 1996), was a\nPakistani politician and leader of al-Zulfiqar, a terrorist organization [http://www.najamsethi.com/murtaza-bhuttos-\ndilemma/ Sethi, Najam: The Dilemma of Murtaza Bhutto, The Friday Times, (1993)]-\n[http://www.waterstones.com/waterstonesweb/products/raja+anwar/the+t-\nerrorist+prince/5493636/ Anwar, Raja: The Terrorist Prince ] operating in\nPakistan. The son of Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, the former Prime Minister of Pakistan,\nMurtaza founded al-Zulfiqar after his father was overthrown and executed in 1979\nby the military regime of General Zia-ul-Haq. In 1981, he claimed responsibility\nfor the murder of conservative politician Chaudhry Zahoor Elahi, and the\nhijacking of a Pakistan International Airlines airplane from Karachi, during\nwhich a hostage was killed. [http://www.historyofpia.com/hijackings.htm\nHistory of PIA: Hijackings] [http://blog.dawn.com/2010/04/09/al-zulfikar-the-unsaid-\nhistory/ al-Zufikar, the Unsaid History, DAWN 2010] In exile in\nAfghanistan, Murtaza was sentenced to death in absentia by a military tribunal.\n\nHe returned to Pakistan in 1993 and was arrested for terrorism on the orders of\nhis sister, then-Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto. Released on bail, Murtaza\nsuccessfully contested elections to the Sindh Provincial Assembly, becoming a\nvocal critic of Benazir and her husband Asif Ali Zardari. After increasing\ntensions between the two, he was shot dead along with six associates in a police\nencounter near his home in Karachi on 20 September 1996. [http://tribune.com.pk/story/439575/death-anniversary-16-years-since-\nmurtaza-bhutto-was-killed/ Mir Murtaza was shot dead by the police in 1996 on\nhis way home in\nKarachi.] [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/7162565.stm BBC\nâ Bhuttos: Cursed dynasty] Benazir's government was dismissed a month\nlater by President Farooq Leghari primarily citing Murtaza's death and\ncorruption. Burns, John F (5 November 1996). \"Pakistan's Premier Bhutto is\nput under house arrest\". The New York Times Zardari was arrested and\nindicted for Murtaza's murder, \"Pakistan ex-premier's spouse indicted for\nmurder\". The New York Times. 6 July 1997. but acquitted in\n2008. [http://archives.dawn.com/2008/04/10/top7.htm Zardari acquitted, DAWN\n2008] [http://tribune.com.pk/story/439575/death-anniversary-16-years-\nsince-murtaza-bhutto-was-killed/ In 2008, Asif Zardari was acquitted of the\ncharges of ordering the murder.] Murtaza's own faction of his father's\nPakistan People's Party, Shaheed Bhutto, remains active in politics.\n","linknr":287,"url":"Murtaza_Bhutto","recorded":1375085041,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Murtaza_Bhutto&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Murtaza_Bhutto&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*"